english:
  title: Prayer to the Thunder God of Universal Transformation
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Thunder and rain fulfill the Resolve—truly they bear the work of nourishing all things. Yet drought brings calamity, and famine threatens the land. With urgent heart I offer this plea, humbly seeking your divine aid and compassion.

    For the hundred grains to ripen, the heavens must send their timely signs. But our virtue falls short, and heaven's anger descends upon us. The sun burns like fire, the earth below withers and cracks. Already the grasses wilt, and what hope remains for harvests?

    In stillness I reflect: when heaven sends disaster, it is because we mortals have sown transgression. In ten thousand affairs of state, can we not falter? Among the common folk in all lands, do all find their rightful place? Our wisdom has limits; how can we fathom all injustice? Beneath the mountains and streams there surely dwell virtuous ones unrecognized. Within the prison walls there surely languish the wrongfully condemned. All these stir the harmony of heaven and provoke its warnings.

    In shame and sorrow, I turn my reproach inward. Though I cannot undo the past, still I strive for what is to come. Now I ascend the jade altar and offer rosy wine. I humbly beseech you—look upon my sincere heart with compassion, grant your mercy. Let the waters rise from the depths and clouds gather on the peaks. Send forth the great rain. Let the forgotten sheaves and scattered stalks receive the gift of bounty and plenty.
  footnotes:
    - The work is a formal petition or prayer (zhào 醮) addressed to the Thunder God, incorporating Confucian self-reflection on moral responsibility for natural disasters.
    - The reference to 'Resolve' (Jiě 解) alludes to the hexagram from the I Ching, suggesting cosmic harmony through proper conduct.
    - The imagery of drought as punishment reflects classical Chinese cosmological thought linking human virtue to natural phenomena.
